	<exercise>
	<title>Simplifying Absolute Value Expressions</title>
	<statement>
		<p>Simplify the expression in the case that <m>x \gt 2</m>, <m>x \lt 2</m>, and <m>x=2</m>, if possible. Summarize your conclusions.</p>
		<ol labels="a" cols="4">
			<li><m>\displaystyle |2-x|</m></li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle \frac{x-2}{|x-2|}</m></li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle \frac{|2-x|}{x-2}</m></li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle \frac{x^2-4}{|x-2|}</m></li>
		</ol>
	</statement>
	<answer>
		<ol labels="a">
			<li><m>\displaystyle |2-x| = \begin{cases} 
					2-x, &amp; \text{if $x \lt 2$}\\
					x-2, &amp; \text{if $x \geq 2$}\end{cases}
			</m></li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle \frac{x-2}{|x-2|} = \begin{cases}
				-1, &amp; \text{if $x \lt 2$} \\
				1, &amp; \text{if $x \gt 2$} \\
				\text{undef.}, &amp; \text{if $x = 2$} \end{cases}
			</m></li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle \frac{|2-x|}{x-2} = \begin{cases}
				-1, &amp; \text{if $x \lt 2$} \\
				1, &amp; \text{if $x \gt 2$} \\
				\text{undef.}, &amp; \text{if $x = 2$} \end{cases}</m></li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle \frac{x^2-4}{|2-x|} = \begin{cases}
				x+2, &amp; \text{if $x \lt 2$} \\
				-x-2, &amp; \text{if $x \gt 2$} \\
				\text{undef.}, &amp; \text{if $x = 2$} \end{cases}</m></li>
		</ol>
	</answer>
	</exercise>

	<exercise>
	<title>Simplifying Difference Quotients</title>
	<statement>
		<p>Observe that none of the expressions below are defined when <m>h=0</m>; don't attempt to evaluate at this value. Instead, simplify as much as possible. Show your work carefully as a sequence of equal expressions seperated with the equal sign. Then try evaluating the resulting simplified expression at <m>h=0</m>.</p>
		<ol labels="a" cols="2">
			<li><m>\displaystyle \frac{(2+h)^2-(4+h)}{h}</m></li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle \frac{\frac{1}{h+4}-\frac{1}{4}}{h}</m></li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle \frac{\frac{1}{(h+3)^2}-\frac{1}{9}}{h}</m></li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle \frac{\sqrt{h+2}-\sqrt{2}}{h} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{h+2}+\sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{h+2}+\sqrt{2}}</m></li>
		</ol>
		<p>These kind of expressions are called <term>difference quotients</term> and play an important role in the development of calculus.</p>
	</statement>
	<answer>
		<ol labels="a">
			<li><m>\displaystyle \frac{(2+h)^2-(4+h)}{h} = 3+h</m> which evaluates to <m>3</m> when <m>h = 0</m>.</li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle \frac{\frac{1}{h+4}-\frac{1}{4}}{h} = \frac{-1}{4(4+h)}</m>  which evaluates to <m>-1/16</m> when <m>h = 0</m>.</li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle \frac{\frac{1}{(h+3)^2}-\frac{1}{9}}{h} = -\frac{h+6}{9 (h+3)^2}</m> which evaluates to <m>-2/27</m> when <m>h = 0</m>.</li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle \frac{\sqrt{h+2}-\sqrt{2}}{h}\cdot \frac{\sqrt{h+2}+\sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{h+2}+\sqrt{2}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{h+2}+\sqrt{2}}</m> which evaluates to <m>\frac{1}{2\sqrt{2}}</m> when <m>h=0</m>.</li>
		</ol>
	</answer>
	</exercise>


	<exercisegroup>
		<title>Working with Exponents</title>
		<exercise>
	<title>Rewriting Powers</title>
	<statement>
		<p>Write each term as a power of <m>x</m> using negative or rational exponents as necessary.
			<ol marker="a">
				<li><m>\displaystyle 3x^4-\frac{1}{x^2} + \frac{2}{x}+1</m></li>
				<li><m>\displaystyle 4\sqrt{x}-5\sqrt[3]{x}+6\sqrt[5]{x^2}</m></li>
				<li><m>\displaystyle \frac{1}{x^5} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{x^5}} - \frac{1}{\sqrt[5]{x}}</m></li>
				<li><m>\displaystyle \frac{2}{x^3}-\frac{x^3}{2} + \frac{1}{2x^3}</m></li>
			</ol></p>
	</statement>
	<answer>
		<ol marker="a">
			<li><m>\displaystyle 3x^4-\frac{1}{x^2} + \frac{2}{x}+1 = 3x^4-x^{-2}+2x^{-1}+1</m></li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle 4\sqrt{x}-5\sqrt[3]{x}+6\sqrt[5]{x^2} = 4x^{1/2}-5 x^{1/3} + 6 x^{2/5}</m></li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle \frac{1}{x^5} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{x^5}} - \frac{1}{\sqrt[5]{x}} = x^{-5}+x^{-5/2}-x^{-1/5}</m></li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle \frac{2}{x^3}-\frac{x^3}{2} + \frac{1}{2x^3} = 2x^{-3}-\frac{1}{2} x^3 +\frac{1}{2} x^{-3}</m></li>
		</ol>
	</answer>
	</exercise>

	<exercise>
	<title>Rewriting Powers</title>
	<statement>
		<p>Rewrite each term without any negative or rational exponents.
			<ol marker="a">
				<li><m>\displaystyle -5x^{1/3}-4x^{-3}+\frac{1}{x^{-3}}</m></li>
				<li><m>\displaystyle 4x^{-5}+\frac{x^{-4}}{5}-\frac{4}{x^{-5}}</m></li>
				<li><m>\displaystyle 4x^{-3/2}+5x^{-2/3}-6x^{4/2}</m></li>
			</ol></p>
	</statement>
	<answer>
		<ol marker="a">
			<li><m>\displaystyle -5x^{1/3}-4x^{-3}+\frac{1}{x^{-3}} = -5 \sqrt[3]{x}-\frac{4}{x^3} + x^3</m></li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle 4x^{-5}+\frac{x^{-4}}{5}-\frac{4}{x^{-5}} = \frac{4}{x^{5}}+\frac{1}{5x^4} - 4x^{5}</m></li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle 4x^{-3/2}+5x^{-2/3}-6x^{4/2} = \frac{4}{\sqrt{x^3}} + \frac{5}{\sqrt[3]{x^2}} - 6 x^2</m></li>
		</ol>
	</answer>
	</exercise>

	<exercise>
	<title>Laws of Exponents</title>
	<statement>
		<p>Simplify each expression, including rewriting any negative or rational exponents. You may assume all variables are positive real numbers.
			<ol marker="a" cols="2">
				<li><m>\displaystyle \left(x^4 y^3\right)^{2}</m></li>
				<li><m>\displaystyle \left(x^4 y^3\right)^{-2}</m></li>
				<li><m>\displaystyle \left(x^{-4} y^{3/2}\right)^{-2}</m></li>
				<li><m>\displaystyle \left(x^4 y^3\right)^{2} \left(x^{-2} y^{1/2}\right)^4</m></li>
				<li><m>\displaystyle \left(\frac{2x^2 y}{x^4 y^0}\right)^{-2}</m></li>
				<li><m>\displaystyle \left(\frac{-2x^2 y^{3/2}}{x^4 y^1}\right)^{2}</m></li>
			</ol></p>
	</statement>
	<answer>
		<ol marker="a" >
			<li><m>\displaystyle \left(x^4 y^3\right)^{2} = x^8 y^6</m></li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle \left(x^4 y^3\right)^{-2} = \frac{1}{x^8 y^6}</m></li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle \left(x^{-4} y^{3/2}\right)^{-2} = \frac{x^8}{y^3}</m></li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle \left(x^4 y^3\right)^{2} \left(x^{-2} y^{1/2}\right)^4 = y^8</m></li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle \left(\frac{2x^2 y}{x^4 y^0}\right)^{-2} = \frac{x^4}{4y^2}</m></li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle \left(\frac{-2x^2 y^{3/2}}{x^4 y^1}\right)^{2} = \frac{4y}{x^4}</m></li>
		</ol>
	</answer>
	</exercise>

	<exercise>
	<title>Laws of Exponents</title>
	<statement>
		<p>Simplify each expression. You may assume all variables are positive real numbers.
			<ol marker="a" cols="2">
				<li><m>\displaystyle \sqrt{64 x^6 y^5}</m></li>
				<li><m>\displaystyle \sqrt[3]{64 x^6 y^5}</m></li>
				<li><m>\displaystyle \sqrt{64 x^6 y^5} \sqrt{9 x^3 y^4}</m></li>
				<li><m>\displaystyle \frac{\sqrt[3]{27 x^6 y^5}}{\sqrt[3]{-8 x^3 y^4}}</m></li>
			</ol></p>
	</statement>
	<answer>
		<ol marker="a">
			<li><m>\displaystyle \sqrt{64 x^6 y^5} = 8 x^3 y^2 \sqrt{y}</m></li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle \sqrt[3]{64 x^6 y^5} = 4 x^2 y \sqrt[3]{y^2}</m></li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle \sqrt{64 x^6 y^5} \sqrt{9 x^3 y^4} = 24 x^4 y^4 \sqrt{xy}</m></li>
			<li><m>\displaystyle \frac{\sqrt[3]{27 x^6 y^5}}{\sqrt[3]{-8 x^3 y^4}} = -\frac{3x \sqrt[3]{y}}{2}</m></li>
		</ol>
	</answer>
	</exercise>

	<exercise>
	<title>Laws of Exponents</title>
	<statement>
		<p>Simplify each expression, including rewriting any negative or rational exponents. You may assume all variables are positive real numbers. 
			<ol marker="a" cols="2">
				<li><m>\displaystyle x^{-2}\left(x^2-x^{-2}\right)</m></li>
				<li><m>\displaystyle \left(x^2+x^{-2}\right)\left(x^2-x^{-2}\right)</m></li>
				<li><m>\displaystyle \left(x^2-x^{-2}\right)^2</m></li>
				<li><m>\displaystyle \frac{x^2-x^{-2}}{x^2}</m></li>
				<li><m>\displaystyle x^{1/2}\left(x^{-1/2}-x^{1/2}\right)</m></li>
				<li><m>\displaystyle \frac{x^{1/2}-x^{-1/2}}{x^{1/2}}</m></li>
			</ol></p>
	</statement>
	<answer>
		<ol marker="a">
				<li><m>\displaystyle x^{-2}\left(x^2-x^{-2}\right) = 1-\frac{1}{x^4} = \frac{x^4-1}{x^4}</m></li>
				<li><m>\displaystyle \left(x^2+x^{-2}\right)\left(x^2-x^{-2}\right) = x^4-\frac{1}{x^4} = \frac{x^8-1}{x^4}</m></li>
				<li><m>\displaystyle \left(x^2-x^{-2}\right)^2 = x^4+\frac{1}{x^4}-2 = \frac{x^8-2 x^4+1}{x^4}</m></li>
				<li><m>\displaystyle \frac{x^2-x^{-2}}{x^2} = 1-\frac{1}{x^4} = \frac{x^4-1}{x^4}</m></li>
				<li><m>\displaystyle x^{1/2}\left(x^{-1/2}-x^{1/2}\right) = 1-x</m></li>
				<li><m>\displaystyle \frac{x^{1/2}-x^{-1/2}}{x^{1/2}} = 1-\frac{1}{x} = \frac{x-1}{x}</m></li>
		</ol>
	</answer>
	</exercise>
